I literally did cite a source. Are you blind? These guys don't even read before they revert, man. Fucking hell.
The WorldWildlife Fund and scientists on platforms such as researchgate tend to use "common leopard".

Do not revert my edits without reason. That is destructive behavior and causes needless edit warring. If you have a problem with my edits, either take it to my talk page or explain why they shouldn't be allowed.

Do not revert my edits without reason. That is destructive behavior and causes needless edit warring. If you have a problem with my edits, either take it to my talk page or explain why they shouldn't be allowed.
All I did was tweak the wording for the sake of consistency. The content of the article still remains the same. In no way was what I did vandalism.
He's not native to England, so no he isn't. Being born in England does not make you English.
/* Description */There's 2 species of ostrich, so the southern cassowary would be the 3rd heaviest.
Please provide evidence of that being a universal rule. The orangutan article contradicts your claim for example.
According to the study linked in the Siberian Tiger article, the Siberian tiger is smaller than the Bengal tiger, so it would not be the largest fully terrestrial predator.
/* Pets and ornamentals */Does not belong here as this is not a general article on all domesticated ducks.
Given the subspecies box, this article should specifically be tailed towards A.p.domesticus.
Plural form should be used since giraffes are a genus.
Turns out I was wrong about type species. My apologies.
Ceratops horridus is an obsolete taxon and therefore not an actual species. It would imply the existence of a genus called Ceratops.
Why are type species described through the usage of outdated taxons? Very odd.
AFAIK only the red jungle fowl can be considered a chicken (or the domesticated subspecies at least).

The current phrasing suggests that there are two species with the binomial name Canis lupus, I believe that my current phrasing more accuratetely reflects that Pleicostene wolves are the same species as modern grey wolves, and are merely a subset.
The hell is "last best" supposed to mean? Don't revert edits for no reason. That is needlessly destructive.

I fail to see why it's not obvious. I removed Simia troglodytes because it's not the proper binomial name of the chimp. There's no genus named Simia. The chimp belong to the genus Pan, so its binomial name should reflect that.\n\nSecondly, I don't think "panin" should be italicized as it's not the name of a genus or species. It's just a way to refer to its members. We wouldn't italicize "dinosaur" either.
"House cat" is not a common name for the species Felis catus as a whole and therefore shouldn't be emboldened.

This has nothing to do with "scientific accuracy" as "dog" is not a scientific name. No idea why you decided to bring up science. Very odd I must say.\n\nSecondly, please provide evidence of people using "domestic dog" as a way to distinguish term. Until you do so I see no reason to accept that I must seek consensus.

You know that you can literally just look up the word prototheria...right? I'm sorry, but this is quite frankly a bizarre reason for undoing my edit. Your lack of knowledge could've been solved by just clicking on the link.
The proper scientific name of the western gorilla is Gorilla gorilla, not "Troglodytes gorilla". Otherwise the implication would be that the genus is called Troglodytes.
Taxons other than species should be treated as a group rather than a singular animal.
/* Phylogeny */Populations. There are only two subspecies of tiger.
/* Leopard */Panthera pardus pardus is a subspecies, not a species.
/* African bush elephant */"African elephant" is not a species. It's a genus. Loxodonta africana specifically refers to the African bush elephant.
Bottlenose dolphins constitute a genus. Common bottlenose dolphins constitute a species.
Cape buffalos are a subspecies of African buffalo, so it can't refer to the entire species.
The genus has its own article.
Unsourced + contradicts another statement made in this article "mean body mass for wolves is 40 kg". That's not compatible with the statement "males weigh 40 kg on average".
Grammar edit. "octopus are members of the order octopoda" doesn't make any sense.

Euarthropoda and Arthropoda are the same taxon, and since Arthropoda is the more commonly used name it should be prioritized. Plus, in the wikibox it's literally called Arthropoda, so using the name Euarthropoda in the introduction is unnecessarily confusing.
There is more than one species of electric eel, so the plural form of eel should be used.
None of those species are actual dogs. They just have "dog" in their name. It's like how flying lemurs aren't actual lemurs.
Not a valid reason to revert an edit. Please do not engage in destructive behavior, or I will contact the moderators so that they can administer your banishment. Thanks.
Domestic dog is redundant. The only animal known as the dog is domestic.
Since Gigantophis garstini does not have a common name,  it is known only by its binomial name. Not the name of its genus
Taxons other than species aren't treated as individuals.
While monotremes do belong to the subclass Prototheria, they are not synonymous with it.
More informative. Most people do not know that Panthera onca means jaguar.
Hitz scored once against Leverkusen in 2014/15.
The title of bats and gorillas are singular as well, but their introductory descriptions are plural in spite of that.
Fixed definition. Defining them as "mammals of the order primates" would make every primate a lemur.
Wikipedia says that humans are a species, not a subspecies, thus their scientific name would Homo sapiens.
He identifies as Gabonese. There's no debate.

/* Etymology and definition */No need to get a consensus for this as this edit further reinforces what the article says. Do not revert without good reason. That is disruptive and I will report you to the admins.

/* Etymology and definition */This edit is pefectly in line with the definition laid out by Wikipedia. (Homo sapiens) Wikipedia itself defines humans as strictly being Homo sapiens, so Homo sapiens is the only human species, not the only "extant" species. I don't see how there's a valid basis for reverting this edit.
/* Etymology and definition */The genus Homo is alternatively regarded as synonymous with "human". Wikipedia describes Homo erectus as "archaic humans".
Since human can refer to either the specific species Homo sapiens or the all-encompassing genus Homo, we should make that clear in the introductory section.

Chickens are red junglefowl, not just the descendants of red junglefowl. It makes more sense to say that Gallus gallus encompasses the chicken. Saying that red junglefowl are the ancestors would be like saying that primates are the ancestors of humans. While technically true, the latter is also a subset of the former.
Being aware of subjective experience is more akin to self-awareness.
Edited wording to further emphasize that domestic chickens are a subset of Gallus gallus rather than being a distinct animal as some might think.
/* Etymology and definition */Edit to acknowledge the second definition.
/* Etymology and definition */While there are multiple definitions of humans, this article seems to go by the colloquial one. I.e. the one that only includes Homo sapiens.

1. My original wording needed some tweaking.\n2. Since this article considers Paleoloxodon species to be elephants as well, it would be more accurate to say that this article is about a paraphyletic group. Also, the paraphyly would make mammoths non-elephants so that would make the second part a misnomer.
The order they belong to is already mentioned in that sentence.
Canine refers to members of the subfamily Caninae.
By definition that isn't true. Humans are defined as the species Homo sapiens. There can't be other species of a species
Archosauriformes is not extinct as it still has living members (birds and crocodiles).
/* Etymology and definition */If humans are defined as the species Homo sapiens, they are the only human species. So it would make more sense to describe them as the only extant Homo species.
No point in making it a link if it just redirects people to the same article. Boldening it makes more sense.
They/them pronouns make more sense when you consider the rest of the paragraph

Added systematic name and specified the type of grouping
Some taxonomists prefer Cetartiodactyla, some want to stick with Artiodactyla.
Though it'd be better to have the short description be more specific.
I really don't think it makes sense to call them hippopotamuses when we already use that term to define the common hippo. When you do call them that it makes the definition of hippopotamus unclear.

1. Short description does not reflect the definition laid out in the article. Whale, in this context, is not synonymous with "cetacean". \n2. Since we're not defining whales in the cladistic sense, it does not make sense to say that hippos are their closest living relatives. Other cetaceans would be in this case, so I tweaked the wording a little.
Tweaked the opening paragraph to include the systematic name.
Amphisbaenians are neither lizards nor snakes.
This would make the article consistent with the "list of lacertilia families" article
Other members of the genus ''Homo'' are often called humans as well. Similar to how pig can correspond to both the genus ''Sus'' and the species ''Sus scrofa''.
/* Last sentence of lede */ new section
Pisces is the scientific name for fish. "Pisces" also redirects to this article in other articles

Tweaked the phrasing a little to have it make add up with the opening paragraph
Animal articles tend to start out with a definition (fx frogs are amphibians of the order Anura), so I think we should do the same for elephants).
/* Size */Species should be treated as individuals.
There is ZERO reason to be combative about this. Living an extant mean the exact same thing, and use of the former is accepted in many articles. This is destructive behavior. Stop it.

Living rolls of the tongue more easily here
Just thought it was worth noting that mastiffs, as far as high end estimates go (hence the "peak weight" thing), are the largest living canids.
The big five revers to species, not types of animals.
They no longer coach Barcelona and Bayern respectively.
Contradicts the part about Hazaras being "racially Eurasian". Hazaras are primarily a mix of East Asian and West Asian (Middle Eastern).

Afghans are not an ethnic group.

This article is specifically about the ethnic group.

Germans are one of the most historically prominent and well-known ethnic groups; I think it's important to acknowledge in the article that they are, in fact, an ethnic group.
Short description contradicts what's said in the article. Egyptians are a genetically distinct ethnicity.

The predominant ethnic group is Syrians. "Syrian" is not a legal term for the nationals and citizens for Syria. Putting Arabs there as the predominant ethnicity is just wrong. Wikipedia even agrees with Syrians being an ethnicity.

Iranians and Turks don't speak Arabic.
English isn't a nationality, and he's obviously not ethnically English. He's British.

Iraqis are an ethnic group, and not just a legal nationality.
Once again, Syrian is not interchangeable with Arab, they are a distinct ethnic group.
Syrians are a distinct ethnic group and aren't just synonymous with Arabs in general.

Please refrain from engaging in linguistic prescriptivism. What you personally think is inaccurate has no bearing on the validity of a definition. "Mandarin" means Standard Chinese in colloquial speech, whether you like it or not.
Please do not engage in edit-warring. Edit disputes ought to be settled at my talk page. Thank you.
Primelephas species are not classified as elephants.

/* Evolutionary history */This article is about elephantids as a whole and not elephants specifically. So the phraseology of "modern elephantids" is more in line with the scope of the article. \n\nAlso, "elephantid" is already used in an earlier line, so to suddenly use "modern elephant" appears to be less sensible.

There are several extinct groups of elephantid that are not considered elephants, so calling Elephantidae "elephants and mammoths" is inaccurate because it neglects two genera, namely Primelephas and Stegotetrabelodon.
Both the informal group of elephants and Elephantinae already contain several extinct members, so this is a more sensible phraseology.
It is already implied that modern elephants are the only surviving proboscideans.
Elephants are specifically a paraphyletic group of Elephantinae, not Elephantidae. Otherwise there would be another genus of elephantid in the "traditionally excluded" list.
"Elephants and mammoths" is not wholly accurate. Primelephas species are also not considered elephants.
Elephants and rhinos are not singular species, so H.amphibius isn't the third largest.

The "also known as" part is unnecessary IMO. Americans are also known as American people, the Chinese are also known as Chinese people, Mexicans are also known as Mexican people, etc etc. I think it's obvious enough to the point where it doesn't have to be spelled out.
Lacertilia is not a legitimate suborder of Squamata. Look at the cladograms for Squamata here and you'll find that no group is called Lacertilia. The title of this article should be changed.

Lacertilia is not an actual suborder of Squamata. If you look at Squamata cladograms, you'll find the groups that commonly make up lizards, yes, but they aren't all lumped together under the label Lacertilia.
Important to make clear that goat applies to other species as well, and that this one can also be called the domestic goat.
The binomial name and the Taxobox indicates that the chicken is classified as a distinct species, not a subtype of another species.
Members of the genus Ovis cannot be all "wild sheep", since it contains the domestic sheep.
No need to try and goad people into thinking Wikipedia is the best site ever. Let them decide for themselves.

1. Chimpanzee refers to Pan troglodytes. While it's true that it can also be applied to Pan paniscus, that's not how the word is generally used.

2. The taxonbox (or whatever it's called) specifies Pan troglodytes, so the article should match the taxonbox for the sake of consistency.

3. You can't hybridize with a genus, you can only hybridize with a different species. The idea of a species-genus hybrid makes no sense.
